[2] Primate infections, Brazil
Date: Thu 21 Apr 2016
Source: BioRxIV doi: http://dx.doi.org/10.1101/049395 [edited]
http://biorxiv.org/content/early/2016/04/20/049395


Silvana Favoretto, Danielle Araujo, Danielle Oliveira, Nayle Duarte, Flavio Mesquita, Paolo Zanotto, et al. 1st detection of Zika virus in neotropical primates in Brazil: a possible new reservoir.

Abstract
Samples from sera and oral swabs from 15 marmosets (_Callithrix jacchus_) and 9 capuchin monkeys (_Sapajus libidinosus_) captured in Ceara State in Brazil were tested for Zika virus. Samples were positive by real time PCR, and sequencing of the amplified product from a capuchin monkey showed 100 per cent similarity to other ZIKV from South America. This is the 1st report on ZIKV detection among Neotropical primates.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Mary Marshall

[This important observation raises several key questions related to the potential the role of marmosets and capuchin monkeys as Zika virus reservoirs: (1) do they develop viremias of high enough titer and long enough duration to infect susceptible mosquitoes? (2) Which mosquitoes feed on these primates, become infected and subsequently transmit the virus to other primates? If a sylvan (forest) cycle of transmission becomes established, similar to yellow fever virus and non-human primates in the Amazon Basin, the virus is here to stay, with occasional spill-over to humans. - Mod.TY]

******
[3] Encephalopathy, adults
Date: Thu 21 Apr 2016
Source: Eurosurveillance [edited]
http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=21452


Roz√© B, Najioullah F, Signate A, Apetse K, Brouste Y, Gourgoudou S, et al, on behalf of the Neuro-Zika Working Group of Martinique. Zika virus detection in cerebrospinal fluid from 2 patients with encephalopathy, Martinique, February 2016.

Summary
We report 2 cases of encephalopathy (one with seizures, one with electroencephalogram changes) in patients with Zika virus infection. The cases occurred on Martinique in February 2016, during the Zika virus outbreak. Awareness of the various neurological complications of Zika virus infection is needed for patients living in areas affected by Zika virus infections or for travellers to these areas.

Case 1
A previously healthy young adult was admitted to the University Hospital of Martinique, after having experienced an episode of convulsive seizures that occurred 6 hours after the onset of a dengue-like syndrome (fever, arthralgia, asthenia and headache). Upon initial clinical evaluation, the patient was febrile, with a low level of consciousness (Glasgow coma scale (GCS) 9) and no neurological focal signs.

Case 2
A patient in their late 70s was brought to the University Hospital of Martinique by their family who reported symptoms including acute mental confusion, speech disorder, and right facial palsy, which had started three hours before hospital admission. Upon initial clinical evaluation the patient was afebrile and aphasic; conjunctivitis, bilateral hands oedema, and peripheral arthritis were present. Facial palsy was not noticed upon clinical examination. Aphasia resolved spontaneously 45 minutes after the 1st clinical evaluation.

In this report, we present 2 cases of encephalopathy fulfilling the diagnostic criteria of the Consensus Statement of the International Encephalitis Consortium. Based on the laboratory findings, we consider these cases as Zika virus-associated. In keeping with neurological findings in other arbovirus infections, the presentations were of non-specific nature; the spectrum of arboviral neurological disease may even lead to ischemic stroke. Moreover, in arbovirus-related neurological disorders, imaging findings may be normal and different EEG abnormalities can be seen. Zika virus is known as a neurotropic microorganism, however, both structural imaging and EEG can be normal in acute infection.

Awareness of the wide spectrum of neurological symptoms of Zika virus infection is needed for patients living in, or travelling to areas affected by Zika virus infections. Knowledge of the pathophysiology of Zika virus infection and the reasons behind its predilection for the CNS is needed to design treatment strategies to mitigate significant morbidity.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[These 2 cases illustrate another facet of Zika virus neurotropism, in these cases, encepalopathy in adults. Subscribers interested in the details of these 2 cases are encouraged to read the entire report. It will be of interest to know whether similar cases have been seen in the countries with the most Zika virus infections, Brazil and Colombia. - Mod.TY]

